Small to medium-sized ( 20–50 mm wingspan) moths, many with brightly colored wings. Th e group is defined mainly by larval characters. Th e adults of many species are active during the day, others are nocturnal, and a few are active both day and night. The adults of many species roost on the larval host plant, in some cases within its flowers. Larvae feed on the reproductive parts of the host plant (sepals, flowers, and seeds). A few, such as the Corn Earworm (
Helicoverpa zea
), are among the most destructive lepidopteran agricultural pests in temperate regions.
